Nov 22 2009 	Awesome	I stayed here for one night last Thursday night. I checked in at 3:00pm and was given a strip room. The rooms are large, very nice relaxing bedding, and oversized bathroom. My future stays in Vegas will be at Planet Hollywood.	
Nov 22 2009 	Awesome Stay at Planet Hollywood	My husband and I stayed at Planet Hollywood from November 17th - November 21st. We traveled to Las Vegas to see a friend make his WEC fighting debut (and he won!). We chose Planet Hollywood primarily because we got a fantastic deal on Vegas.com, and also because the reviews here at Trip Advisor were largely positive. We arrived at Planet Hollywood at about 6:15 pm on Tuesday evening; there was nobody waiting in line, and we were greeted and checked in right away by Trina, who was a big help. We had booked a 'Hollywood Hip' room with the 'Drinks Are On Us' promotion, which gets you a voucher for a bottle of liquor, wine or champagne from the gift shop. We asked about fountain-view rooms, and were able to get not only a fountain view but also a larger-sized Resort Suite for an additional $30 per night. The room was fantastic--better than I expected. We were on the 22nd floor, directly across from the Bellagio Fountains and had a view of the strip facing North. We could see the Bellagio, Caesar's Palace, the Paris, the Mirage and Rio all from our room. Although I had requested a King non-smoking, they only had the Resort Suite with two queen sized beds, which was fine. The room had two comfy, purple velvet lounge chairs, a large flat screen TV and a very big bathroom with dual vanities, large soaking tub, separate shower and private toilet. The room also had an office desk and chair, which hubby took over with this laptop and work stuff. The movie memoriablia in our room was from &quot;Beverly Hills Cop III&quot;. Lame! Our room was kept very clean during our stay. On our first morning, we noticed that one of our bedsheets had an odd stain on it. We left a note for Housekeeping pointing to the stain and asked them to please change the linens, and when we had returned later in the day it had been done. The bathroom was kept very clean and well stocked with towels, washcloths and little toiletries (shampoo, conditioner, skin lotion). I had read a lot of reviews that said the quality of the towels was poor, but ours were quite nice. In fact, they were a little bit linty--maybe new? The TV stand itself was kept very tidy, but the glasses and ice bucket were dusty, as though they hadn't been used or changed out in maybe a week or so. We never used them, so it didn't really matter. Our room's carpet was a little bit worn in the high traffic area in front of the beds, and had a couple of 'pulls' that made it look a bit shabby, but it was kept very clean during our stay.The hotel itself is really a cool place. It's also kept very clean and looks well-maintained. We never saw a single stain on the carpet, burned out lightbulb or signs of neglect or wear. The casino is huge and circular-shaped. We got a kick out of the 'Pleasure Pit', where the tables also have pole dancers. The girls are lovely and wear fun, costume-y outfits and dance to current pop and rock music while you gamble--awesome! They really love to portray the image of Hollywood and celebrity, as if celebrities come and stay there all the time. The hotel is full of crystal chandeliers and disco balls and is definitely geared towards the younger, hip crowd. There's music playing everywhere, all the time, and there is no shortage of 'beautiful people' who come to play, especially at night. We ate breakfast two mornings at Planet Dailies, a 24 hour coffee shop and restaurant located inside the Casino. We really enjoyed our meals here on both visits. They have a large menu, quick service, great coffee and fresh squeezed orange juice. I highly recommend the Moco Loco, the Breakfast of Champions! We also ate lunch once at the Spice Market Buffett, which was pretty unimpressive for the price. I would skip this one--go over to the Bellagio for their lunch buffet and prepare to be blown away. Wish we had! The Casino also has a full-sized, 24 hour Starbucks and several other restaurants and bars. We ordered room service one evening and took advantage of the &quot;Drinks Are On Us&quot; voucher. There is a great selection of liquor, wine and champagne--I think most anyone could find something they like. The room service menu is very large, and includes items from PF Changs, located inside the Miracle Mile shops at Planet Hollywood--yum! The meal arrived exactly when promised, hot and fresh, and was very good. It's also nice and very convenient to have the Miracle Mile shops attached to the hotel. There is tons of shopping. Convenience stores, clothing, restaurants, bars, ice cream...you name it, it's there. We were hit up many times during our stay about getting 'comped' because we were staying there, but the shows / tickets they were offering weren't all that interesting to us. Most times, a simple 'no, thanks' was all that was needed and they left us alone. We were only approaced once by the timeshare folks, but we never felt chased down or harrassed by anyone. The weather was not quite warm enough for us to be tempted to use the pool area, although there were a few die hard sunbathers out there during the days we were there. It seemed okay, pretty clean looking, but hard to tell how it would be since it is not the busy season.I read several reviews of Planet Hollywood that had concerns about air qualtiy in the hotel. I can tell you that I did notice that walking through the hotel hallways and in the elevators, the faint smell of cigarette smoke is always present. We are not smokers, and live in Austin, where smoking is prohibited most everywhere, so coming to Vegas is a little bit of a shock to the system, so to speak, as smoking is allowed most everywhere. We would expect the casino to be a bit smoky, and it was, although not overly so...but the hotel's ventilation did not seem to do a great job filtering it out. The air is extremely dry in Vegas to begin with, and every morning hubby and I woke up with sore throats, plugged sinuses and itchy eyes. Neither of us suffers from allergies of any kind, but it's hard to say whether what we experienced was truly the climate in Vegas or the hotel's air quality. It did make me wonder a bit, is all. Truly the only thing that was disappointing about Planet Hollywood was the walkway in front of the casino, which is under construction. There is a temporary walkway set up with concrete barriers, so walking is safe and out of traffic, but the walkway is clogged with those folks that 'flick' the porn cards at you. It's so annoying! Not to mention, the walkway is literally papered with those little cards, because people just take them and chuck them. It's kind of a shame--it's not really Planet Hollywood's fault, but it is really, really dirty along that stretch. I know that the sidewalks get covered wherever those folks are handing anything out...it's just particularly bad in front of Planet Hollywood. Tough to walk through that walkway every night also, knowing that you had to pass through the endless 'porn corridor' to get back to the hotel. It's not the content that bothered me (it is Vegas, after all), it's just the annoyance of their presence and the stupid litter they cause. We had to laugh, though, because at the very entrance of the porn corridor was a little man with a bell and a Salvation Army donation kettle, standing there diligently ringing his bell standing right next to the porn peddlers. Hats off to him! Overall, I would definitely stay at Planet Hollywood again, no question. We had a great time!	
