Nov 11 2009 	There are many other far better places nearby. Skip this one.	I wanted to like this hotel but I have to say I was extremely disappointed. I booked this hotel as part of a conference stay. Since we came in to town a few days early, we booked a really cheap rate at a Candlewood Suites for the weekend and then moved to the Planet Hollywood for the next three nights since the conference was there. There’s a world of difference between the low budget Candlewood Suites and the Planet Hollywood, but in comparing the two…I felt like the Candlewood Suites was a huge enjoyable bargain and I felt really ripped off at Planet Hollywood.Planet Hollywood is highly stylized and a bit over the top on some things. The casino is nice and the food at the Spice Market Buffet was actually pretty good and reasonable. The only other thing I liked was the movie memorabilia in each room. (Inside a glass case in my room were a flight helmet prop and baseball cap used in the filming of the 1991 film called “Flight of the Intruder.” So while that was very cool….that was about the only thing the room had going for it.Even getting into the hotel is not easy. It is in the slot on the strip that the old Aladdin Hotel was in and they never really did a good job in using signs to help guests driving south down Las Vegas Blvd. how to turn to the proper street to get back to the entrance of the hotel….which is hidden way back off the street on the back and underside of the hotel. Unlike other strip hotels where the self parking is reasonably close to the hotel (after you make the obligatory walk through the casino to get to check in) the Planet Hollywood makes you park in the self parking (luckily for free) and then walk through a huge shopping mall called the Miracle Mile and THEN through the casino and THEN down escalators to the front desk on the lower level. It is not well laid out or signed so that you can easily tell how to get around inside. Of course they want you to get lost in the maze of slot machines so that you might give up trying to find your way and give up some money to the one armed bandits.The rooms are extremely dark. There are a total of 5 low wattage lights in the room and in my room, one of them didn’t work. The window is about four feet by five feet so there’s not a lot of ambient light. At our conference one of the presenters said he complained to the front desk and they gave him a flashlight saying they give out hundreds of flashlights per week to guests. If you are going to do that, why not just leave them in the room in the first place.The beds were way cheaper and less comfortable than the one at the Candlewood Suites room I stayed in the night before for a fifth of the price. We knew it was not going to be good when my wife and I walked into the room and sat at the very end of the bed and it actually made the head of the bed come off the ground about a foot…that’s how cheap the bed frame was. I actually thought if we weren’t careful we were going to break it. It was that rickety and squeaked loudly when you moved in the bed. The sheets were also thin and uncomfortable. Plus they come untucked way too easily. Our first night we ended up in the morning with a real mess of sheets and mattress pad that kept me awake. Rather than a soft mattress pad, they use a thick wool blanket like covering under the sheets which is really hot and not very soft and comfy. I honestly think the managers here haven’t just stayed in one of the basic level rooms…if they did, they’d see it really is not that plush for the price they are charging. The rooms were clean and smelled okay. There’s a decent sized bureau with two large closets and plenty of room to unpack clothes. There is a free in room safe, which was a comfort.There’s also a very prominent large flat screen TV in the room but it’s not in HD and the channels were actually a bit fuzzy for such a large TV….so another missed opportunity there.The bathrooms featured a glassed in shower and a Roman soaking tub. But the tub was not quite big enough for two. Come on…this is Vegas…if you are going to have a soaking tub, have one big enough for two! There was a real full sized bath mat but only two bath towels that were thin and cheap feeling. I had a much better towel at the Candlewood Suites. The amenities came in little round jars with metal screw off lids. The shampoo came out fine but try getting conditioner out of a round jar. You had to stick your fingers in and dig out conditioner which was awkward. What’s wrong with plastic bottles that you can squeeze? I didn’t get the reason for the jars but they didn’t work well. While the bathroom was nicer and newer feeling, the shower took a long time to get hot and the water pressure was anemic. I could probably spit harder that the shower water came out.The Internet service costs $14 a day. They have both WiFi and a LAN connection. The WiFi kept bouncing me off the internet on the first night. It was very inconvenient to have to keep reconnecting, but it worked fine the next two nights. Once connected the service did feature very high speed.The hotel charges a $5.93 daily ‘resort’ fee which pays for your daily paper, two bottles of water in the room and use of the pool. The paper is the Las Vegas Review-Journal, which has only basic coverage of national and international news (not the USA Today which most hotels carry). While we did get the two bottles of water the first night, we didn’t get it the next two nights.You should definitely NOT in any way bring children to this hotel. The current show in the theatre here is called “Peep Show” and is a striptease act. There are big ads for the show all over the hotel, including huge photos on the elevator doors and in the rooms. And, in the surrounding blocks immediately around the hotel are several ‘gauntlets’ of people in very bright T-shirts advertising outcall services promising a “Girl to Your Room in 20 Minutes or Less.” They hand out stacks of business cards with photos of nearly completely nude women on them. They are very aggressive and are all over the place. People take the cards and throw them on the ground….making trashy litter of cards of nearly completely naked women all over the place for several blocks up and down the strip from the hotel. It really is disappointing that the city doesn’t do more to try to keep this out. Prostitution is NOT legal in Clark County where Las Vegas is. Granted this is Las Vegas, but people walking down the strip do not need to be bombarded by swarms of these hawkers with their nearly X-rated business cards that promote something that is not even legal here.So I expected much better from such a better brand. They tried hard to be stylistic and appeal to a younger, hipper crowd. But along the way, the hotel operators forgot that people want to stay at a place that is at least comfortable. Maybe the high roller rooms are more plush, but the basic rooms certainly are not.If you are considering staying on the strip and are going to shell out several hundred dollars a night, you can make yourself happier by skipping Planet Hollywood and staying at the Parisian right next door which is really, really nice or even better at the Bellagio right across the street. If those are both 5-star hotels, then this one barely deserves two and a half.	
