Sep 27 2009 	Nice hotel great location!	Stayed here for 6nights from 16th Sept and already I'm looking at same hotel for next stay. The hotel is one of the more modern on the strip having been refurbished in 2007 and it does show. All parts of the building are bright and airy, the casino floor is one of the most open around and although it's not themed as such compared with others, there's still plenty going on to look at and keep everyone entertained. Myself and my girlfriend had booked a king size room, but upon checkin this eas unavailable, but we weren't disappointed with the double queen room we received. It was on the 36th florr with a great view of the bellagio fountains and the strip, the room was much bigger than any other standard room we had stayed in and was very clean. We thought that this hotel was aimed at younger people, but after staying we think it is more than suitable for everyone, the rooms are well insulated from the noise, the restaurants are fantastic and the location can't be beaten. Most of the main attractions and sights are within 5 minutes walk, plus some of the best bars and shows can be found in and around this hotel. The only down side for us was the staff could be a little un helpful, it seemed to depend on when you asked them for any help that affected what reaction you got, the earlier in the day the more helpfl they were and the later(longer they were working!) the less they could be bothered to help. But don'tworry as very few things go wrong here, just go out and enjoy the vegas experience!	
Sep 26 2009 	Party Time!	Plenty of reviews here - but here's my 2cents.Firstly, I would just like to say that when you stay at PH you are mainly paying for one thing: Location, location, location. Don't come here expecting exceptional service where your every need is catered too. Some people in these reviews act like that because you are paying a premium you should be treated like a VIP, nagana happen. You are paying for the privilege of staying at PH. If you want to be catered to, try the Skylofts. Another note for the newbie, don't bring your kids. I can't believe how I was tripping over kids sometimes. Hello? This is an adult hotel. Pleasure Pit, hello?We've stayed here twice. 1) The room. Both times, we stayed in a Strip Suite, we loved the room and it had an outstanding view. The bed was super cozy! Housekeeping did a great job during both stays. The bathroom is great! Of course, the closet is tiny and cannot fit everything. Room had two huge flat screens, and a separate sitting area. The room averaged about 220/night.On one visit we had the &quot;Good Will Hunting&quot; themed room which displayed memorabilia like a jacket someone wore, beer cans from the bar scene, still pics, etc. The other time we had the &quot;Universal Soldier&quot; room, showcasing a big poster of Dolph Lundgren, clothes, and weapons! 2) The Casino. We think it's the best looking casino in Vegas. The pleasure pit is a gem! The decor is fantastic - not granny feeling like the big B. Game play was good. had no trouble finding lower limit tables so we could lose our money slower. Drinks came around at a reasonable pace. Definitely a party atmosphere.3) Bars. Staff did a good job of acting like they were happy to see you, for the most part. Some were even downright friendly! There were some sourpusses and weird attitudes behind the bar - but not a big deal, we don't let the little things ruin our vacation like it seems to do for others. There is the Heart Bar, which is directly in the middle of the casino, hence the name. Then there is the Extra Bar on the edge of the casino. You sit there, put money in the machine like a dunce, talk to people, and drink. Good times.4) Restaurants. The Strip House. Way overrated and way overpriced (except for the oysters, those were incredible (TIP: you can order the same oysters from the room service menu. If you like oysters, I HIGHLY recommend you give these a try)). The decor of the place is very cool, had a 20's feel to it. We went once, we won't be back (we paid twice as much for a dinner at the Eiffel Tower Restaurant next door - worth every penny).Yolo's. Great Mexican food, reasonable price, we will be back.Planet Daily's. Nothing special.Earl of Sandwich. Quick AND Delicious!Spice Market Buffet. Only ate there for breakfast - 'twas delicious.Tip for a cheap breakfast: There is a mexican restaurant down Miracle Mile that has breakfast for $1.99. It's cheap if you only drink water, coffee and OJ will make it about $8. I ordered three breakfasts, two for me and one for wifey. Took the sting out of the Prive bill! (see below).Club Prive. We wanted to go to Prive but it was closed, only the section called &quot;The Living Room&quot; was open. It was a good time. Drinks are ridiculously expensive. I went two the bar and ordered a drink for me and wifey. The bill? about $30Poker: Poker room was good. Well, it was good for a while then everything went to hell when I lost everything. Typical scene - out of towners and a few locals looking to clean you out.Pool: The pool is very bland and desolate. Definitely needs a major overhaul. Overall a great stay both times. If you want a party atmosphere, this is a great choice. Just don't get your expectations too high about the service and everything should be fine. - we will definitely be back	
Sep 25 2009 	Newer but just OK for me	BOTTOM LINE UP FRONT: Busy place, but check in was fast and easy. The rooms are dark and movie theme decorated. You can tell this is a high turnover place because the rooms are getting tired and worn even though the place is only a few years young. Iron, ironing board and safe provided, but NO coffee maker, NO fridge, and NO microwave. Even though I was careful to research to all the fees charged (disclosed when you reserve your room online), I still got hit with an unexpected $5.99 per day for daily newspaper and bottled water replenishment. Amenities are basic and sparse…iron, ironing board, shampoo, conditioner, lotion, two bottles of water. I won’t stay here again unless I have to. If you are a member of Starwood Preferred Group of Hotels my preference would be to stay at the Casuarina which is just off the strip. It’s quieter, the amenities are better dollar for dollar, and you earn the same amount of points. The biggest thing you’ll sacrifice is that the pool at the Casuarina is dinky in comparison. Not sure I’d stay here again.PARKING: Far but free. According to the concierge the garage belongs to the Miracle Mile (mall). That mall is attached to Planet Hollywood (PH) and the garage is attached to the mall. Therefore you have to either walk through the mall and into the casino to get to your room OR go all the way downstairs and dodge the taxis until you get to the check in desk area. It took me 10 minutes to get from 4th floor parking to my eighth floor room.ROOM: On the small side. King size bed, desk and large hutch. Hutch had two small closets on right and left side with a 42 inch flat panel in the middle. Ironing board and iron in one closet. The iron is cheap and leaked water instead of bursting steam. Room was dark with only four lamps (2 bedside, one desk, one floor) to light it. Bathroom was huge with separate shower and large, deep tub for two. Basic shampoo, conditioner, and lotion provided.FOOD and OTHER AMENITIES: In house restaurants offer good food. PF Changs delivers consistently good food, Planet Dailies is open 24/7 with a decent menu but a bit overpriced (e.g. $15 sandwiches), and a #1 rated buffet whose attraction is having food choices from all over the world. Outside the casino is the Miracle Mile mall with numerous eateries as well. If you get a chance to get a coupon book, get one…it has some money saving offers that might be worth your while, but remember that you have to spend money to save money.POOL: Overrated. Two pools separated by a large sunning area, bar, and grill. One pool has no rental cabanas. It is relatively small considering the number of people staying at the hotel. I found this one gets all the early afternoon sun and starts to get shaded at about 4pm. The other pool is laden with rental cabanas and gets the later afternoon sun. Unlike some other pools, there was no DJ during the week so it felt like going to a neighborhood community pool.FITNESS: Cost is $25 per day, unlimited spa area access. Overall it was decent for basic workouts. Numerous cardio machines spread about but free weights are relegated to about a 12x12 area with two adjustable benches, a limited number of dumbbells/free weight, a squat rack and a compact cable crossover station. The spa was OK. You could get a locker, robe, and slippers and enjoy the wet or dry saunas or hot tub. Break area offered free fruit and beverages. After showering, some basics like lotion, deodorant, shaving cream were also provided. I expected more/better.SERVICE: Good. The staff was helpful, on-the-spot, and professional. The only place I encountered less than courteous service was at the Planet Dailies lounge. I only saw my waiter once – not a single offer to refill drink. I didn’t even have silverware or napkin. Basically he took my order then left. I suspect because I was dining alone and drinking only water that I was not a “profitable” customer for him. I tipped him accordingly.	
