Sep 18 2009 	Great rooms good price and awesome staff!	I booked your standard room for three nights at the Planet Hollywood Resort and Casino in Las Vegas. I tend to book the cheapest room possible when I'm in Vegas because, after all, you don't go to Vegas to stay in your hotel room the whole time. I want rooms that are cheap and quiet (and where I can sleep in until 3 in the afternoon if I want to). I paid about $50 a night through hotels.com.After arriving late at night, I was offered a free upgrade to one of their suites by the front desk. I thought that perhaps he had upgraded me to a room with a strip view, but I had been upgraded to the biggest hotel room that I had ever seen. The room itself was simply stunning. It came with three large flat panel tv's, a huge party room, a great view overlooking the Bellagio fountains, and an air hockey table (which, surprisingly, was the source of much fun).The hotel room itself was great. It had very comfortable beds, great water pressure, and was very quiet. I couldn't have asked for a better room in Vegas.My biggest complaint is with the casino. I'm an engineer and so I study what rules give the player the biggest edge. The rules at Planet Hollywood (especially for blackjack) are not favorable for the player at all. I would head down to the Tropicana or Excalibur if you want to play games that have rules that benefit the player more. The casino is also very loud (I tend to like casinos that are a little bit more quiet). As a side note, the sports book area is very nice. There are a lot of comfortable couches in there where you can watch any game that you've wagered money on.Overall, there's something for everyone at Planet Hollywood. I would definitely stay there again (even if they didn't upgrade me to the suite).	
