Sep 8 2009 	Enjoyed the stay	We arrived at around 11:00 p.m. at the hotel. There was virtually no wait to check in. We had the &quot;Drink on Us&quot; promotion, and our deal included several other upgrade (average nightly rate was $149). They promptly checked us in - our rate included a fountain view upgrade, but the only fountain veiw was a room with two queens as opposed to a king...no problem for us. They also explained the free bottle program (a free brand named bottle of booze, wine or champagne each day) and provided the coupons for the other promotions.There was no wait for the elevators, so we found our room quickly and were pleased to find a decent sized room, with a large bathroom with an oversized tub, separate shower, separate toilet, nice toiletries and tons of high quality towels and washcloths. Also, the view of the fountains was fantastic.Over the course of three days, we never waited for elevators, we found plenty of options in the casino (and left with more money than we came with), were served frequently and with high quality service and product while gambling. We used the gym, which was normally priced at $25/day or a 3 day pass for $60, and was well equipped and clean. The pool was nice, but not terribly large. We ate at three places in the hotel - Yolos (very affordable, high quality mexican fare), twice at Planet Dailies (a huge, diverse menu, very tasty and very affordable), and once at the Spice Market Buffet for breakfast (decent selection, decent food...we don't normally do buffets, but had a freebie coupon).All in all, good location on the strip, very good service, good casino, well equipped hotel for most anything you'd want to do. We would stay there again.	
Sep 8 2009 	Mix of good and bad: Great location worn out rooms	My wife and I stayed in this hotel in our trip last August. My sister recommended this hotel to us. She forwarded me an email offering a room (with free bottle of drinks every night!) for only $59. The catch is you have to pre-pay for the first night. I thought why not, we have booked our Vegas flight anyway.The lobby located at the hotel basement feels glamorous. They restored the lobby such that you really feel like a rock star that's about to check-in. However, you'll feel otherwise once you join the long queue of people checking in. Never mind that. They allowed us to check-in early at 10am. (They actually offer a guaranteed early check-in for $25 in the reminder email they send days before your stay. There is no need for you to go for this offer. If you'll go in a low season, chances are, you can check-in early anyway.) The catch was that they only have rooms in the smoking floor. We settled for it anyway, we thought it shouldn't be that bad.The room was clean and as promised in their website, it has a Hollywood memorabilia that is unique in every room. The bed was comfortable and there's an LCD screen TV as well. But the bad thing is that the room really reeks of cigarette smell. We have stayed in smoking rooms before, but it didn't really smell this bad. Perhaps the hotel's exhaust system isn't that efficient anymore.Deciding that we may not survive inhaling second-hand smoke for the next two nights, I asked for a transfer in a non-smoking room. All rooms were occupied except for an accessible room. We have taken the room without bathtub anyway.After a few minutes, we are at our new, non-smelly accessible room. Great! It looks clean, though we thought the room could use extra lighting. The rooms in this hotel were just too dark. Even the light at the desk isn't working—they fixed it anyway after I told them about it. It is quite a challenge to adjust the temperature of the AC as well. The AC unit looks very old.We were warned that it can get a bit flooded in the shower area. I didn't understand what they mean until after taking a shower. The water drips beyond the shower curtain which can flood the rest of the bathroom. We have to use extra towels to stop the water for seeping. If the hotel is aware of this anyway, it would have been great if they rectified it.Our general impression of the room is that it looks really tired. Perhaps when they renovated the old Aladdin hotel, they only refurbished up to the lobby area. More could be done to improve the feel of the rooms, in my opinion.The location of the hotel is great. You can access a lot of neighbouring hotels and casinos in minutes. The Miracle Mile mall is just below for those who just want some retail therapy.Planet Dailies is a good choice if you want to eat in this hotel. The 24-hour restaurant offers a nice spread of Western or Asian options. The service is fast and they are always helpful.Spice Restaurant is deemed to be one of the best buffet restaurants in the Strip. We thought it is just ordinary. No dish was really outstanding. Good thing is our lunch here is free--some Westwood timesharing we attended to for 2 hours gave us free buffet in this restaurant (and $50 for Planet Dailies!).The hotel also has a mini-mart at the check-in lobby floor where you can grab your water, snacks and drinks. It is convenient, but it will be cheaper if you get stuff from the nearest Walgreens or 711.You can secure cheap room rates if you will either subscribe to their newsletter, or be their Twitter follower, or be their fan at Facebook. Perhaps because of its location, this hotel will still be on top of every budget-hunting traveller. I will only recommend this hotel because of its location. I don't really expect much for a $59/night rate. I just hope they improve their rooms.	
