Aug 9 2009	Great Stay at Planet Hollywood!	This is the place to be if you're under 35. There is a nice energy in the Casino and it's decor is modern/trendy... it doesn't really have a theme other than &quot;chic.&quot; The rooms are nice... we had two &quot;Hollywood Hip&quot; smoking rooms both had clean white bed linens (hard to hide anything with white linens) and a very spacious bathroom. Each room has a 42&quot; plasma TV (though there aren't that many TV stations available), a giant tub, separate toilet area, glass shower, desk, chair, etc. Each room also has a theme with movie props--we had two rooms the &quot;Little Buddha&quot; room and the &quot;Life Stinks&quot; room. I've never watched either movie so I couldn't be in awe of the props but it was still something that you don't find in most rooms on the strip.The only drawback of the location was that there is a lot of construction going on across the street (therefore the street was blocked off creating a bigger than normal traffic issue on this part of the street). The Lobby and Valet/Parking Garage are located one floor lower than the Casino and the Casino itself is large enough to get lost in but small enough to find your way back and very clean (no finger prints all over the slots or empty glasses everywhere). There are plenty of places to eat &amp; shop in the Miracle Mile Shopping Center, though most of the shops are places that you can find at your local mall. For a quick and cheap bite (I use that term loosely since most food in Vegas is a bit more expensive than at home) I'd recommend the Earl of Sandwich--fresh and buget friendly at $6 per sandwich (though the $2.50 Pepsi is a bit steep) and located on the border of the casino, it's a great spot to grab a quick hot sandwich. The elevators have flat screen TVs on the roof and there are a ton of elevators for each tower so that you never have to wait for a long time or ride in a crowded elevator. The halls are a bit plain but quiet. This is a great hotel for everyone except children. There is a Pleasure Pit at night with girls dancing on poles (way more tame than it sounds but not exactly your Grandma's Vegas) and mostly younger crowd--the casino does get crowded but it's still easy to find an empty slot machine... this might be good or bad depending on what you're looking for in a hotel &amp; casino.All in all the Planet Hollywood is a great bargin and fun place to be!	
