Aug 6 2009 	Fits its price point	Friends of ours decided to make a trip to Las Vegas and asked us to join. We frequent the Venetian, but they had already booked at the Planet Hollywood. After a call to a PH casino host, we were set to join them.As themes go, they have definitely improved the place from its days as the Aladdin. The common areas are all very chic, and it is clear that they are targetting the younger Vegas crowd. The lobby area is eclectic and very cool. The casino is laid out well (although it is easy to get turned around, typical of any casino). During the evening hours there is a definite energy in the place. It's unpretentious and enjoyable. The music is better than any place on the strip, and really got you motivated to play. The dealers were a bit of a disappointment, as most lacked the personality of those at other resorts. I found player ratings to be very inconsistent, which is the reason I most likely won't be back. If you are a gambler, beware, and make sure you regularly check with the pit boss to make sure you are being rated fairly. Drink service is above average in the casino, and excellent if you tip well. The sportsbook is relatively small, but there are several small tables and chairs with their own flat panel. This is great if you are with friends and want to catch a game. The manager at the book was great, but I found the other employees to be rude.The pool(s) are small, and get packed early. You need to be out there when they open in order to ensure that you get a spot, unless you have arrangements for a cabana. There is a large &quot;garden&quot; area in between the two pools which you can usually find chairs at, but they are not poolside. Drink service is average.We had a Resort Vista (all the suites had been reserved), and it was average at best. The view was OK, facing the strip, but directly toward the unfinished CityCenter. The bed was very comfortable, but the overall layout was not very good. There are no closets, and the armoire only offers limited space to hang clothes. The fixtures appeared to be worn and almost dirty. The bathroom was large, but bare, and didn't appear to be very clean. The maid service did their job, but also broke a pair of my sunglasses (knocked them off the vanity). I sent a memo to management regarding this, which went unresponded.The hotel offers a decent selection of restaurants, which ranged from average to good. The Earl of Sandwich is definitely worth a visit if you are wanting a quick bite.Westgate, which owns the tower next to PH, has timeshare folks all over this place. I found it to be very second rate. They literally approached us at every turn. They were quick to cease if you said you weren't interested, but to be hassled by this on a casino floor is ridiculous.Overall, it's a fun casino to play in. If that is all you are looking for, then this is a good CASINO for you. If you are concerned with Player Ratings and comps, the fun just doesn't make up for the poor ratings. As far as the rooms, it depends. It beats the rest of the South strip with the exception of Mandalay Bay and MGM, but can't compare with anything Bellagio and north. It just isn't luxurious and clean enough for me to part ways with other Vegas hotels, but with a younger crowd and ambiance, it's worth a stroll through.	
