Jul 10 2009 	Not the best not the worst . . .	We stayed at the hotel for three nights, our room on the 29th floor had a great view of the Strip. A couple of items in our room were broken or not functional when we arrived, but a friendly maintenance man fixed them in short order. The room itself was a nice size, the bathroom large.PROS: Price was very reasonable, location on the Strip is convenient, free bottle of wine or spirits each night of our stay.CONS: Parking is difficult, although there is &quot;free&quot; valet parking available. You must pay $14 per day if you want internet access (or go down to the Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf in the Miracle Mile for free WiFi). There are no garden areas like many of the other hotels.I guess my biggest gripe about Planet Hollywood is the architecture and interior design. They are trying to turn a themed hotel (the Alladin) into Times Square meets hip, sleek, and cool. That works nicely in the rooms, but not so much in the public areas. The street side of the hotel has got to be the ugliest on the Strip. The Miracle Mile shops are beginning to look like your neighborhood mall. I know the Moroccan theme isn't what PH wants and it was a little Disneyesque - but it was fun and it's becoming bland.Other than that we were very satisfied at Planet Hollywood.	
Jul 10 2009 	Great Stay @ Planet Hollywood!!	We had a great time here!! It was our 2nd trip to Vegas and choose PH this time because we found an amazing deal with Virgin Holidays.Check in was fine, we arrived around 2pm on a Tuesday and there was no Q. We had 4 rooms and wanted to get some connecting, this wasn't possible as we also wanted 1 smoking room, so we settled for rooms near each other. We managed to get one room with a fabulous Fountain View - Beautiful!! The rooms were large &amp; well equipped, large TV &amp; HUGE bathroom. Little closet space but we knew that and found there was enough room for all of our clothes (we took our own hangers).The Casino is not the biggest, but there are many entrances/exits onto the Strip &amp; Miracle Mile Shops but by day 4 or 5 we had our bearings!!We had the Buffet for breakfast, it was massive &amp; reasonable at $15. All types of food there. (We also did Caesars buffet which was $26 and TINY). We grabbed sandwiches at The Earl of Sandwich regularly and they were great, very quicky made too and reasonable.We also did bottle service in Prive, we were a little disappointed as the bottle prices were higher than we had been quoted &amp; found that our Waitress was far more attentive to her male customers around us than she was with us. (understandle I suppose).Regarding the main things people complained about with this hotel - We were only approached by the timeshare people ONCE in the Casino, I guess this is because we were a group of 20 something girls and do not really look the types to buy...Our room was quiet near the lifts and the only time I heard a &quot;DING&quot; was when I was standing by the room door.Lighting in the room is dull, however lighting in the bathroom is more than adequate for putting on your make-up.Overall we found the hotel fab and would recommend it to anyone, we would stay again!!	
Jul 9 2009 	Planet Hollywood is in a downward spiral.	This hotel once was absolutely great, now it is just another mediocre hotel on the strip. I have stayed here for 8 years even when it was the Aladdin, so I know a thing or two about this hotel. The pools are at best marginal and if you like getting your bags searched at the pool you will love the pool areas. The new clientele here apparently likes to smuggle booze into the pool area. This could be because of the 10.00 Rum and cokes.There is also some nice astro turf that has been added, really classy. They blocked off about 1/4 of the pool area for $250.00 a day Cabanas which are hardly ever used. This means there are more people on the concrete atrium area than around the pool. This makes no sense at all. Do not expect to sit around the pool in this hotel. It is the biggest farce of all. There was no security at the pools so watch your belongings and do not bring kids here. With the lower rates a new clientele has arrived. This is not a good thing when they are drunk and misbehaving in the pool areas and in their rooms. Two nights we got no sleep because of boom boxes playing music next door. No security ever came to help with this. It is simply a matter of economics, clientele that stay for $59.00 a night are different than the clientele that was paying $159.00. This is why I loved this hotel before, but not now. The gamblinghas been jacked up also. Do not expect any 10.00 BJ tables, most are 15.00 and 25.00. It was a good place to play BJ but not anymore. A lot of single deck and higher limit tables. Bellagio has quite a better mix of tables. They kick you off the BJ tables at 8:00 if you do not up your BJ bets to 25.00 because of some girl dealers that have no idea what they are doing. They are hired for looks not dealing skills. The slots are so tight they squeak. We ended up at different hotels every night to gamble, so why stay here. Check in is a nightmare even if you are a platinum member. The upgrades have become non-existent because of the lower rates and influx of people and now they are offering the upgrades to the public for 25.00. It is not worth the trouble to stay with Starwoods here. I actually had more fun at the Golden Nugget in April than I had here in June. If you are lucky you will get a spectacular view of the alley and the mountains 75 miles away. If you liked the Planet Hollywood before, go to the Bellagio. It still has its values in tact.	
