Jul 7 2009 	Great Stay	Stayed at PH from July 2-6th, 2009 with my wife and another couple along with another group of friends in another room at the resort. Vegas veterans (5-7 trips). Mid-late 20's, mix of couples/singles. Take note when I write a review I tend to get long-winded so I'll break it down to make reading easier:Check-in... Noon Thursday with about 4 people in line and 4 attendants checking people in (needless to say it was quick). I asked, note asked no tip required, the attendant if we could get a room with a view of the fountains and he ended up putting us on the 25th floor...2587 (note the resort has 51 floors). I also asked if our friends could be placed near our room for convenience and they made a note on his reservation (they ended up on the 26th floor). I had signed up for a promotional rate and we received coupons for free bottle service per night stay, some nightclub admission tickets, and spa passes. We were NOT hassled by any timeshare people after check-in or during our entire trip. Room... We had the &quot;A Time to Kill&quot; room and it was nice, but the view is what got me... fantastic! The bathroom is nice and large (no fan though kind of weird). The room is dark, and there is limited space for 4 people but we managed. Two complaints about the room (I'm a male so the darkness really didn't affect me as much as the ladies)... 1) A/C in the room just doesn't really get cold enough for my taste and 2) Limited outlet space in the room for cell phones/IPod's/etc especially with 4 people. Other than that we used the room to sleep, mix drinks, and watch a few fountain shows from on high so it did the trick! Free newspaper and 2 bottles of water per day ($5.59/day resort fee) were issued. I tip maids a few bucks so maybe that's why we never had an issue with this.Pool... I knew going into this that the pool area was not going to be great, and it wasn't. It doesn't make sense how such a nice place would have such a flaw. Pool area opened at 10:00. Wife went down at 10 to get chairs, and one day had to wait in line. We had decided that we'd use the late morning as a relaxing time to mill around the pool. Chairs around the north pool were almost always completely full by 11 am. There is a north and south pool, and in the middle kind of a no-mans land with loungers and astro-turf that'll burn the bottoms of your feet it's so hot so watch out! DJ spins music starting at 11 am with trendy pool music, nice atmosphere, cold pool. Again not great but the pool wasn't one of our priorities just a place to spend a little time to try and relax.Restaurants... Day 1 we ate lunch at a Cheeseburger joint in the mall which was pretty good. We had dinner at the Strip House Steakhouse with a promotion for Peep Show, it was fantastic. It was not crowded, but we ate at 6:30 pm (early for vegas standards). Day 2 we ate breakfast at the Spice Market Buffet ($10 w/coupon book) and it was good, not great. Lunch was Earl of Sandwich, for $6 you get hot sandwiches... great stuff we grabbed sandwiches a couple times from here. I also had coffee in the mornings from Illy and Coffee Bean, both good and not overpriced with huge lines like the Starbucks in the hotel (both in the mall as well). There are too many restaurants to list here, but suffice to say anything you could imagine you could find to eat and eat well in the resort. A+ in my book for selection/price/taste.Bars/Casino... There was so much to offer in the casino, all the latest slots, every table game you could imagine (even some in the &quot;Pleasure Pit&quot; with girls that met the criteria for working there), and ample bars to either chill/relax or go party. Heart Bar, Extra Lounge, Halo to sit and mingle, Prive to party (with a different promo each night), Hawaiian Tropic for karaoke or more casual party. A hip crowd with vibe to match, all around great place to hang out and made it hard to think about leaving.Mall... quick review of the mall. I don't want to stereotype, but the mall was more suited to my kind of shopping. Sure there were high-end shops, but the majority were geared toward the non-high-roller. Nothing gets me pumped up like walking past Louis Vuitton, D&amp;G, Armani, etc etc etc and not even thinking about setting foot in them (note sarcasm). Stores in the Miracle Mile had the hip and sometimes eclectic feel, but always felt inviting rather than the heavy glass doors, fancy upscale feel, and hands-off approach of the stores mentioned above. If you want to just stroll, people watch, and actually shop the mall at PH was pretty awesome. Also plenty of restaurants in the mall to choose from, a laser show (pretty boring), and rain storm (eh sort of neat), and ABC stores for beverages/food items if you desire at good prices.Check-out... did it by TV, simple as pushing two buttons!Overall... I'd give PH a 8/10 only because of the pool or it'd have been near perfect. I'm the planner in the group so I knew what I was getting into and the PH delivered on virtually all accounts. Were never hassled by timeshare people, maybe we got lucky in that regard but a group of 10 and none of us got the pitch (with 3 couples). Great atmosphere for 20-30 somethings, people were awesome, great stay! Enjoy!	
