May 23 2009 	If the Price is Right - Great Place!	We stayed at P.H. May 10-15. We got an excellent package deal through Allegiant Airlines out of Bellingham. Arriving in the evening, check in was quick and efficient. We were given a non-smoking, king sized room (as requested) overlooking the south strip. The bed was very comfortable and we loved the roomy bathroom with separate toilet area. Hotel has easy access to the Miracle Mile mall (ask at customer service for their coupon book) with plenty of shops and restaurants. That's what we liked about P.H. - now for what we didn't like.Internet access costly; dark rooms, resort fees (which all of Vegas seems to charge). We were shocked that people were smoking in the hallways when we had a non-smoking room. Ashtrays were provided by the elevators, inviting smokers to light up. The music in the centre casino area was so loud it grated your nerves and we just wanted to get out of there. (Most of he go-go dancers looked bored stiff.) Slot machines in a back area made no noise at all so they didn't create any excitement. They were the stingiest slots anyway, so we soon went gambling elsewhere. We were given a coupon book with discounts for dining, etc. We went to Planet Dailies coffee shop and although the prices were on the high end thought the coupons would compensate the difference. Once we were seated we noticed food arriving in baskets as though it was a drive-in. No thanks! We left and didn't try any other P.H. restaurants. We found several in the mall that were more reasonably priced. There are plenty of hotel deals going on so we'd stay somewhere else if we return.Tips on Vegas - we happened to used Ritz shuttle service from the airport. This company didn't take credit cards though so be prepared to pay cash. We paid for a return trip and they were prompt at pick up time. We took the shuttle bus to the outlet mall in Primm using a 2-1 coupon found on the internet. We did find a few bargains. We bought day tickets for the monorail which cost $26 for 2 - NOT worthwhile in our opinion. You can only access a few stations and you still walk miles to get to anything. A bus pass is a far better option. We also dislked the fact smoking is permitted virtually everywhere in casinos. Vegas is behind the times as several countries have smoking bans in public places. They should at least have non-smoking areas in casinos.We haven't stayed in Vegas for years, and overall we found the 'new' Vegas to be expensive with it's designer/brand shops, celebrity chef restaurants and high priced shows. We missed the old Vegas with loose slots, inexpensive food and a fun atmosphere. There are still some bargains but you need to search and use coupons. The good news is we won't complain about the prices in London anymore!	
