May 19 2009 	Prime Strip Location!	I went May 14 - 17 with my boyfriend and we had an awesome time! Planet Hollywood is a really funky place and the location on the Vegas Strip couldn't be better. We went through all of the hotels on the strip within the weekend and were never far from home whereever we went. Rooms: Really nice even though we didn't have a very good view. I didn't request a strip view or anything, and the only time we were in our room was to nap/sleep/get changed so I didn't really care. The bed was super comfortable, the bathroom was really quite huge (seperate shower, bath and the toilet had it's own door too). The lighting, as others have said, can be a bit dim. But during the day I found the daylight to be more than enough for anything we needed to do. There are 4 really bright lamps in the room too, and I don't think we ever had more than one on at a time when we were winding down for bed. Also I never heard a peep from the elevators or other rooms. I found it quite quiet, but I wasn't too close to the elevators so I can't speak for those rooms.Room Service: was good. Came back and everything was clean and we had stuff replenished (hand cream, towels, etc.). Pool: We only spent a bit of time at the pools because we were busy doing other things, but let me tell you it's like a giant pool party. Huge shallow pools (I guess they don't want the drunks drowning) and music bumpin' hot tunes. Lots of pool chairs around and lots of booze too. It's a very young scene I wouldn't recommend this hotel for people over 40 maybe... I felt bad for the 50+ people who were trying to relax poolside with a bunch of drunken crazy 20-somethings splashing around haha. Food: At the PH, we only ever ate at the Spice Buffet. It was very good but it's regular $30/person so use your $5 coupon to make it $25/person and it's a bit more reasonable (we're cheap so that was our fanciest meal haha). If you're looking for cheap breakfast I recommend La Cantina in the Miracle Mile Mall, it was really delicious. You don't always have to eat at buffets either, you will find fast food joints in some of the cheaper casinos (Subway, Burger King, Pizza &amp; Taco places etc. ). As others have said the ABC Store in the Miracle Mile Mall is a good place to get water. We bought a couple of two litre bottles for cheap so we always had water in the room. You can even refill your smaller bottles so you don't have to buy them when you're walking around.Cheap Drinks: If you're looking for drink bargains, go to your right when leaving the hotel. A ways down you'll find Bill's Gamblin' Hall where a dude outside sells $3 Coronas (you can bring them everywhere with you, in and out of every casino/bar) and Bill's has $1 Margaritas and cheap pitchers as well. Casino Royale and O'Sheas are other cool/cheap places to drink... they're more pub style and rugged but we fit in more at those types of places more than we would at any club. Cheap beer is all we're after. If you head the other way on the strip (South) you'll find a lot of mini marts and such. Pick up a six pack and drag it around with you and you'll never be beerless. It's a good alternative when you're not near a cheap bar. Transportation: I was going to look into buying us the $7 Deuce bus All Day passes for each day, however it turned out we didn't use it once. We walked everywhere... you will spend a LOT of time walking in Vegas. Bring comfy shoes. Comfort over style is key... or you'll be sorry. Failure to follow this rule will result in blisters, sore legs and a lot of whining and missed fun. Transportation to and from the airport we just got cabs. There was a lot line for cabs at the airport but it went incredibly fast... they have a whole system. Fare is about $13-$15 to PH. P.S. you will need the bus to travel to the downtown area if you're going... it's pretty far and supposedly not the nicest area. But in general, walking everywhere is fun and free!Stuff To Do: If you're there during the week, go see Big Elvis at Bill's Gamblin Hall from 3:00 - 7:15. He's got a great voice and it's free. Get there early to get a seat, he's very popular. The Lions at the MGM is pretty cool. I felt terrible for them at first (there are two usually at a time) but then we found out that there are a total of 38 and they will bring them in from a Lion sanctuary close by... so really one Lion probably goes once a month or so. And they seem to have fun... the trainers play with them and get really close... It makes me wonder if there's ever been any maulings haha. That'd be scary. We checked out the shark reef at Mandalay Bay which costs about $16/person. It's pretty cool, I'd say it's worth it. The Bellagio fountain shows are also pretty. General Tips: Like I said, wear comfy shoes or sandals that you will be able to walk in for a long time. You'll thank yourself for doing so. Also, the air is really dry in Vegas. I found with a lot of walking around outdoors my nasal passages, throat, eyes, hands... everything... got really dry. Problem solved by using hand cream, saline nasal spray, eye drops and drinking water. If you don't bring these things, hand lotion is in your room and eye drops and nasal spray can be picked up at Walgreens. It really helps soothe. All in all - Come here if you're in your 20's - 30's looking to have an awesome time. It's full of young people and although it's pretty fancy it's very casual. Stay here for the location and value alone! It's awesome!! Email me if you have any questions... I'll try and answer as best as I can.	
